Restoring the very American ideal that labour rights are human rights at the same time
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis have proposed a bill to protect union organizing as a civil right.
“The way unions work, jobs work for the middle class,” says Ellison, a Democratic senator from Minnesota who is co-chair of the congressional committee.
That's why I'm so proud to be able to introduce a law that strengthens the status of employees, along with John Lewis's model of occasional rights.
This ground-breaking legislation will give workers the same legal options to prevent discrimination when organizing in trade unions as other forms of discrimination – and will stop anti-union forces
To amend the Labour Relations Act to allow all employees who face discrimination if they want to engage in trade unions to be tried in civil court – and to judge compensation or compensation for damages – is a right and necessary initiative.
But this is certainly not a radical initiative - at least not according to American standards.
The best way to understand what Ellison, Lewis, and other proponents of the law are proposing is to re-attach the American ideal.
Despite the trade union struggles that have taken place in recent years — in Wisconsin, Michigan, and other states — Americans once supported countries around the world to embrace, expand, and respect labor rights.
There have been times, and millions of Americans still remember, when the country with one breath promoted democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press, and the right to assemble.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas MacArthur and his advisers supported the country to adopt a constitution designed to ensure that Hideki Toja's military autocracy would be replaced by democracy.
They were convinced that employees and their unions played a role in the formation of a new Japan, incorporated language into them, and openly recognized that “the right of employees to assemble, collectively negotiate and act is guaranteed.”
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his advisers urged the Germans to create a constitution that would ensure that Adolf Hitler’s fascism would be replaced by a strong democracy.
The Germans realized that employees would need to organize and promote themselves in the new nation, and therefore included a clause that openly states: “The right to create unions that will secure and improve working and economic conditions will be guaranteed to every individual and every profession or profession.
Arrangements that will limit this right or seek to damage it will be cancelled. Measures leading to the fulfillment of such purpose are illegal.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt presided over the International Commission on Human Rights, which proposed the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, which was adopted by the United Nations in 1948 as a worldwide treaty, the drafters and Roosevelt included in it a guarantee that "every person has the right to exercise his or her rights."
For generations, Americans have accepted the basic premise that labor rights are human rights.
When the country advised other countries how to create civil and democratic society, the Americans explained that the right to create labor unions – and their participation in collective bargaining with companies and government agencies as an equal partner – must be protected.
Now that these rights are being challenged in America, it is imperative to return to the American ideal that working people must have the right to organize and promote themselves in a free and open society.
As the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Today everyone knows that the trade unions did not reduce the strength of the nation, but expanded it.
They have raised the standard of living of millions of people, created a market for industry and raised production to an undisguised level.
Those who attack trade unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History does not forget and neither should we.
The formal recognition of labour rights as human rights - and the extension of the protection of civil rights in order to prevent discrimination in the organisation of trade unions - has come a long way.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis are renewing the ideals that have lifted America and made it a true promise of democracy.
