How many dimensions can our universe have?
The idea that our universe may have more than three spatial dimensions may sound crazy, fantastical, strange, or mystical.
Yet it is concrete and completely acceptable.
To understand this, let’s turn our gaze for a moment from the universe as a whole to something more earthy, specifically to a long and thin garden hose for watering.
Imagine pulling a hundred-meter garden hose from one side of the canyon to the other and watching the whole scene from half a kilometer away (as in the picture and on the next page).
From such a distance, you can easily notice a long hose stretched in the horizontal direction, but if you do not suffer from sharpness, you will hardly recognize the thickness of the hose.
Because of its great distance from the hose, you would think that the ant forced to live on the hose has only one dimension in which it can walk: the left-right dimension along the hose.
When someone asks you where the ant was at a given moment, you will only answer them with one data: the distance of the ant from the left (or right) end of the hose.
All we want to say is that from a distance of half a kilometer, a long piece of hose looks like a one-dimensional object.
In the real world, the hose is thick.
If we enlarge everything, we suddenly see a second dimension - in the shape of a circle wrapping a hose.
In such an enlarged view, it is clear that the ant can in fact move in two independent dimensions: in the already well-known left-right dimension along the length of the hose, but also in the "dimension in/against the direction of movement of the hour hands", that is, around the circular cross-section of the hose.
You begin to understand that to determine the position of a small ant you need to enter two numbers: how far it is from the end of the hose and where there is on the circle wrapping the hose.
This reflects the fact that the surface of the hose is two-dimensional (note that experts will notice that this chapter focuses purely on the fault theory of strings.
Non-disruptive aspects are discussed in Chapters 12 and 13.)
The surface of the hose is two-dimensional: one long longitudinal dimension is represented by a straight arrow, the dimension in the direction of the circumference, marked by a circular arrow, is short and curved.
However, there is a clear difference between these two dimensions.
The size along the hose is long and easily visible.
The size of the casing of the hose is short, "turned" and worse noticeable.
To realize the existence of a circular dimension, we had to examine the hose with a significantly better resolution.
This example illustrates the important property of spatial dimensions.
The fact that they are divided into two groups.
They can be either large, large, and therefore directly visible, or on the contrary small, twisted and much worse observable.
Of course, in this case, we did not just pretend to reveal the "turned" dimension covering the thickness of the hose.
Just take a telescope to help.
But if the hose were thinner - like a hair or a capillary - we would only reveal the twisted dimension with great effort.
In 1919, Kaluza sent Einstein an article in which he expressed the astonishing idea that the spatial geometry of the universe could have more than three dimensions known to all of us.
Kaluza justified his radical claim by providing an elegant and convincing framework in which Einstein’s general relativity and Maxwell’s electromagnetic theory can be woven into a single, unified conceptual structure.
The question immediately arises, how does this Kaluz observation come together with the obvious fact that we see exactly three dimensions of space.
The answer, which Kaluza quietly assumed between the lines and which was clearly pronounced and clarified by Swedish mathematician Oskar Klein in 1926, stands and falls with the claim that the spatial geometry of our universe can have both large and curved dimensions.
This means that, like the dimension in the length of the hose, our universe also has large, vast and easily visible three dimensions, the existence of which we are aware of at every moment.
But, analogously to the circular circumference of the garden hose, the universe can also have an additional dimension, firmly screwed into a space so small that so far it has remained hidden from our most perfect experimental apparatuses.
To get a clearer idea of the essence of Kaluzov's remarkable proposal, let's stay with the hose for a while.
Imagine that we draw a fairly dense series of circles on the perimeter of the hose with a black color.
From a distance, the hose still looks like a thin one-dimensional line.
With the telescope now thanks to the drawing, we will reveal the curved dimension even more easily, because we will see the motif from Figure 2.
We can clearly see that the surface of the hose is two-dimensional, with one dimension large and almost unlimited, and with the other short and circular.
Kaluza and Klein came up with the idea that our universe has a similar structure, but in addition to one small circular dimension, it has three large spatial dimensions, together four spatial dimensions.
It is difficult to draw an object with too many dimensions.
To help our imaginations a little, let us note the illustrations in Figure 3; it shows two large dimensions and one small circular dimension.
In the picture we enlarge the view of the geometry of the space in the same way as we enlarged the surface of the hose.
Each subsequent level represents a huge increase in the geometry of the space from the previous level.
Our universe may have additional dimensions (we see them at the fourth level of magnification) if they are twisted into a sufficiently small space; thus we explain that we have not yet directly observed them.
The square grid represents the commonly known "big" dimensions, while the circle represents a new, tiny and curved dimension.
Just like the loops of thread in a densely woven carpet, even these circles exist in every place of the usual dimensions - just for the sake of visibility, we have drawn them only into the intersections in the square grid.
The background of Figure 4 depicts the commonly known structure of space – the ordinary world around us – in such ordinary scales as the meters, shown on the side of a small square in a square grid.
In each subsequent image, we focus on a small area of the previous image; we enlarge it to become visible.
At first, nothing strange happens, as we see at the first few levels of magnification.
However, when we move on to the microscopic properties of the geometry of space further - to the fourth level of magnification in Figure 3 - we suddenly see a new, curved dimension in the shape of a circle, similar to a string in a densely woven piece of carpet.
Kaluza and Klein came up with the idea that an additional circular dimension exists at each point in the direction of large dimensions in the same way as the tube has a circular circumference at each point of its length.
For the sake of clarity, we have drawn a circular dimension only in some regularly spaced points.
Figure 4 summarizes Kaluzov and Klein's idea of the microscopic structure of space geometry.
The similarity with the hose is obvious, although we also notice important differences.
First, the universe has three large, far-reaching spatial dimensions (of which we have drawn only two), while the hose has only one large dimension.
An even more important difference is that we are now talking about the spatial geometry of the universe itself, not just some object inside the universe, like our hose.
But the basic idea is the same.
If the additional circularly curved dimension is extremely miniature, recognizing it - as well as the circular circumference of the hose - is much more difficult than observing the obvious, large and large dimensions.
If the size of the additional dimension is small enough, it will in fact reveal it beyond the power of our most modern enlargement tools.
Most important, however, is that the additional dimension is not just a rounded sphere within the normal dimensions, as the two-dimensional illustration erroneously suggests.
A circular dimension is a new dimension that exists at each point of three common large dimensions.
It is the dimension of the remaining three dimensions independent as well as the dimensions of the top-down, left-right, and front-back independent (and perpendicular) of each other.
A sufficiently small ant could move in all four dimensions, and to determine its position we would need four data, in addition to the three usual ones still in the circular dimension; if we count the time, then the data five, in any case one more than we would normally expect.
