To our surprise, then, we find that even though we are aware of the existence of only three dimensions of space, Kaluzov and Klein’s thinking that this does not exclude the existence of additional curved dimensions, if they are small enough.
The universe can have more dimensions than we can see with the naked eye.
How small should they be?
State-of-the-art technical equipment can recognize the structures of a billionth of a billionth of a meter.
We can hardly observe a smaller curved dimension.
In 1926, Klein combined Kaluz's original idea with several ideas from the emerging quantum mechanics.
His calculations suggested that the additional circular dimension might be about the size of one Planck length, far beyond the distinctiveness of today’s instruments.
