Genetic disorders are often misdiagnosed
A British woman describes how, after a poor diagnosis for many years, she thought she would die.
After being diagnosed with another disease, Karin Rodgers spent most of her adolescence thinking she only had a few years to live.
In fact, it was Charcot-Marie-Tooth syndrome (CMT) - a group of hereditary disorders that damage nerves outside the brain and spine.
The charity CMT UK said that poor diagnosis is a common problem among people with CMT because very little is known about the disease.
It is believed that in the UK, about 23,000 people suffer from CMT, which can manifest symptoms in the area of motor skills such as muscle weakness, restless walking and twisted toes.
Patients may also experience numbness or pain, this condition is incurable and progressive, which means that over time the symptoms worsen.
When Rodgers was thirteen, she thought she was suffering from Freidreich ataxia (FA), a disease that had a very poor prognosis.
She believed that before she celebrated her eighteenth birthday, she would be chained to a wheelchair, and dead before she was thirty.
The mother of two, who is now 51, says: “As a child, I knew I couldn’t do the same things as everyone else.
I fell every day and it took me longer.
I could never ride rollerblades or skateboards with other kids, and I was bullied at school for the way I walked and ran.
When Rodgers was thirteen and after several surgeries to loosen her Achilles tendons and straighten her feet, she took advantage of the fact that her doctor had left the room and looked at her documentation, where she learned she was suffering from FA.
“I felt guilty because I was stalking, so I didn’t tell anyone, but when I got home, I looked up information about the illness in the library and wrote to the FA Association,” she says.
When they answered, I was in shock, completely panicked.
I thought that by the time I was eighteen, I would end up in a wheelchair, and by the time I was twenty-five, I would be dead, and in the meantime, I would gradually lose all my abilities.
I was all alone, and I was planning a funeral.”
When she was seventeen, she realized that her walking ability had not deteriorated as much as she expected, and she asked her surgeon about it.
He just stood up, hugged her, and said, "Sweetheart, I don't think you're sick, or you'd be in a wheelchair.
I think it’s going to be a lot less life-threatening.”
After a few genetic tests, he was found to have CMT.
“When he explained to me what CMT is, I thought I was a lucky kid,” she said.
The charity CMT UK has launched a month of awareness about CMT to draw attention to this disease.
Washington Businessmen: With the Turn of the Economy, Taxes Are Raised
The growing economy means more customers, higher sales and new jobs.
And also higher taxes.
According to a new survey published last week, the state and local taxation of companies in the country with accelerating economic recovery last year rose slightly and companies in Washington were no exception.
Businessmen in Maryland and Virginia combined in fiscal 2013 took $27.6 billion into state and local treasuries, up 3.8% from the $26.6 billion collected in 2012.
Last year’s tax burden – both state and local – rose 4.3% to $671 billion compared to 3.9% last year, and was the third consecutive year of growth after 2009 and 2010, when taxes fell.
According to a study conducted by Ernst & Young and the Center on State Taxation, state taxes increased by 4.3% faster than local levies by 3.9%.
More than half of the county's tax revenue, 56%, is from trade tax, and 36% of Maryland's income is from corporations.
Virginia, at 28%, has the relatively lowest tax revenue from business.
The researchers argue that the majority of tax revenue growth comes from an increase in the value of real estate owned by companies, which increased property taxes by 3.7% this year after three consecutive years of growth of -1 percent.
Although most of the profits come from big states like California, New York and Texas, it seems the same situation is in Washington.
Companies in D.C., Maryland and Vriginia paid over $10 billion in state and local property taxes last year, up 4.2 percent year-on-year from $9.6 billion in 2012.
However, the apparent increase in real estate value does not push up state and local tax revenues in Maryland, where property tax accounts for less than a fifth of corporate taxation.
For businesses in Virginia and D.C., property tax accounts for nearly half of state and local taxes.
“Maryland owns a lot of real estate companies, especially the tax base around D.C., the government or non-profit organizations that don’t pay taxes,” said Douglas Lindholm, executive director of the Center on State Taxation.
So Maryland is forced to rely much more on income taxes, for example, to pay for the same services that are in other states.
The recent increase in tax revenues from business cannot be attributed only to the healing real estate market.
According to the data, the income from the business also seems to be increasing.
Companies in the region have announced a $2.3 billion corporate income tax, up from $2.1 billion in 2012.
Maryland has raised $1 billion in corporate income taxes, the most in the region.
Even though they are heading in the same direction, local business tax burdens are not growing as fast in these three places.
The growth rate in D.C. was nationwide, at 4.3%, while Maryland’s growth was significantly higher, at 4.9%.
In Virginia alone, the tax increase was below average, at 4.1%.
Virginia has the lowest corporate income tax rate of 6% of all three districts (all of which have the same tax rate).
Maryland’s corporate tax rate is 8.25%, while the D.C. average remains relatively high, at 9.975 percent.
A similar study conducted this year by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce found that Virginia has lower state and local taxes and a generally more favorable tax climate than Maryland.
The D.C. study did not evaluate.
Despite this advantage, Virginia faces the pressure of competition from the south.
North Carolina recently signed a law reducing corporate tax from 6.9% to 6%, as did Virginia, and next year the tax will be reduced to 5%.
If the state continues to meet income targets in the coming year, the income tax rate set by law in 2017 could be reduced to up to 3%.
According to a recent study, small business owners in Washington are doing better, and so are paying higher state and local taxes.
The labor tax levied on small business owners as a personal income tax — the structure of compensation for rising costs by raising prices, according to which most companies are organized — in D.C., Maryland, and Virginia rose 20% last year to $2.4 billion, much faster than others.
The researchers argue that the trend and nationwide increases in trade tax are likely to continue next year, with total sales tax revenues for state and local governments increasing to 6.2% compared to the same period last year in the first three quarters of 2014.
Washington, however, may be lagging behind others, because cutting government spending is taking its toll on the labor market.
